======================================================================
RELATIVE HOMOLOGY VIA BETTI NUMBERS
======================================================================

--- n = 5: LES analysis ---
  β₂(T) distribution: {0: 5120}
  χ(T,T\v) distribution: {-1: 440, 0: 3840, 1: 840}
  β₁(T\v) distribution: {0: 3200, 1: 1920}

  For β₂=0 to work inductively, we need:
  H₂(T,T\v) = 0 for some v, equivalently: H₁(T\v) → H₁(T) is injective
  (when β₂(T\v) = 0 by induction)
  This means: every 1-cycle in T\v remains non-trivial in T.
  I.e., deleting v doesn't kill any 1-cycles.

--- Is H₁(T\v) → H₁(T) injective? ---
  β₁(T\v) ≤ β₁(T): 4280/5120
  β₁(T\v) > β₁(T): 840/5120
  *** β₁ can INCREASE under vertex deletion! ***
  This means H₁(T\v) → H₁(T) is NOT always injective.
  So H₂(T,T\v) ≠ 0 is possible when β₁ increases.
  But we need H₂(T,T\v) = 0 for the proof to work.

  Is there always SOME v where β₁(T\v) ≤ β₁(T)?
  YES: there's always a vertex v where β₁(T\v) ≤ β₁(T).

Done.
